Curug Benowo, curug yang dilupakan.

Karena letaknya berdekatan dengan Curug Lawe yang (lebih) terkenal, pengunjung di Curug Benowo ini jumlahnya timpang dengan jumlah pengunjung Curug Lawe :( Untuk mencapai curug ini, dibutuhkan hiking kurang lebih 2,5 km dari lapangan parkir. Lamanya tergantung kecepatan masing-masing, tapi karena kadang suka macet (jalannya kebanyakan berupa dinding pembatas antara jurang dan gorong-gorong berisi aliran air dari curug), mungkin saat weekend bisa jadi lebih lama dari rata-rata.

First time visiting a beach in Japan!

This is Miho no Matsubara in Shizuoka. The beach looks so so, but it is actually famous as one of the best spot to see Mount Fuji. Unfortunately, today is cloudy so I don't get to see Mount Fuji (again). The beach is not so far, 30 minutes from Shimizu Station by bus. I guess this place is not very popular among tourists, so everyone in here seems like local people who reach the beach by private cars.

The beach is so quiet, peaceful, and surrounded by tree (So I can have a picnic under the tree!) P.S: On the way here, I met a very lovely Japanese @sayo0213. Thank you for accompanying my 2 hours trip from Tokyo to Shizuoka! Hope you have a good time in your hometown :D

#daysinjapan #EPICwestjapan #shizuokaseries #shimizu #shizuoka #mountfuji #fujisan #mihobeach #mihonomatsubara #beach #vitaminsea #passionpassport

Kagetsudo Melon Pan!

There are so many stories behind this melon pan. I was lost in the crowd of Asakusa because of this. But eventually, I found the store and bought three of them.

According to some reviews in TripAdvisor, this is the best melon pan in Japan (whoa). Well, it sure is! It's very soft and... fluffy? And it has just the right amount of sweetness so it's so hard to stop eating. It's also very big, the size is almost the same size as a kid's face.

Definitely worth to try!

caption.text:
Tokyo.

First thing comes to mind: so this is how it feels to be in the biggest metropolitan area in the world.

It's so dense that it can be dense enough to have any kind of people inside it.

Just 300 m out from Shinjuku Station, I already spotted a crowd of people trying to take a picture of someone. I have no idea who he is, maybe politician... or comedian. No idea.

Found 5 people playing Pokemon Go while crossing the street (And I've just walked for 800 m). Tokyo is so crowded, stressful, people passing so fast through your eyes in a super high speed.

But it's beautiful. It has its own beauty which is a whole different kind of beauty that mountains or lakes or beaches have.

Interesting.

caption.text:
Fujisan Series!

Today I rent a bike to go around Lake Kawaguchi (around 19 km) and it is truly the most wonderful experience ever! Even though I didn't get to see Mount Fuji at all because of the clouds (Thanks clouds! Thanks) and it was raining all day (Fortunately, I bring my 100 yen raincoat from Daiso), but so far, the biking is the highlight of my crazy trip. It took me 4 hours to go around the lake because I stopped in so many places to take pictures.

Biking around Fuji is sooo recommended. I recommend you to bike around rather than taking the bus, because the feeling is completely different. You got to see the whole lake, from south to north, east to west.

caption.text:
First stop: Toyota Commemorative Museum.

I do not expect that a tour in this museum is so worth it! The museum is very nice (and the air con is nice too, btw). I learned a lot about the history of Toyota, who started it and how it develops until it becomes one of the most famous auto-mobile company in the world.

The museum is full of high-end technology that you can only see in big factories and, of course, full of super cool cars.

My second favorite museum after Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum!

caption.text:
Good morning!

Starting from today until the next 4 days, I will post about my trip in the West and East Japan area (Osaka-Nagoya-Hamamatsu-Shizuoka-Fujisan-Kanagawa-Tokyo) by JR local train hopping, alone.

After witnessing amazing sceneries of rural Japan, lot of ricefields and wooden houses along the railway from Osaka to Nagoya, I finally arrived in the city of Nagoya.

I always thought that Nagoya is a city as big as Osaka (at least not so different). But unlike Osaka, along Gifu to Nagoya, there are still lot of ricefields.

Well, I guess my crazy trip will start in 3... 2... 1... #daysinjapan #EPICwestjapan #honshuseries #nagoyaseries #nagoyastation #nagoyaeki #trainhopping #explorejapan #explorenagoya #passionpassport

caption.text:
This symbol is called Nazar Boncuğu which means "the evil eye bead". It is believed that this symbol can deflect the negative energy that is being directed towards a person onto itself. Nowadays, people do not use Nazar Boncuğu as a protection from evil only, but also for souvenirs. That is why this symbol can be seen everywhere and can be used for anything. As for me, I am totally in love with this symbol because of the color of the eye pendant.
